  abstract = {The surface pressure of a planet's atmosphere influences its habitability, as it determines whether surface water can exist as a liquid. Surface pressure can evolve over many timescales, from the rotation period of a planet to its entire lifetime. One process that can affect surface pressure is impact cratering. Unlike most other atmospheric alteration processes, impact events can both deliver and remove gasses from an atmosphere. Whether the surface pressure will increase or decrease due to a single impact event depends on the characteristics of both the impactor and target. An open question remains: do atmospheres shrink or grow due to the net effects of many impacts? {$<$}P /{$>$}In this work, we study the net effect of a bombardment period's worth of impacts at Venus, Earth, and Mars. We use a Monte Carlo approach, randomly choosing the size, velocity, and volatile content of each impactor. The consequences of each impact are calculated using 7 different published models, as well as a composite model that we construct from the individual models. We use a variety of initial atmospheric pressures, including present-day pressure and a range of paleopressures from the time of a potential heavy bombardment period. {$<$}P /{$>$}We find that the models from the literature produce final atmospheric pressures that disagree for the same input parameters, sometimes by many orders of magnitude. In addition, if naively applied, several models produce nonphysical results. We suggest more impact processes should be incorporated into these models, and that modern hydrocode modeling should be undertaken to create a new, more accurate model for the change in atmospheric pressure resulting from impacts.},
